Source: tg2sip-webrtc
Section: comm
Priority: optional
Maintainer: Vlad Vorobyev <vlad.vorobev@gmail.com>
# dev/ntgcalls branch package list (see debian/rules for the full story).
#
# Compared to the old tgcalls/tg_owt-based build: libabsl-dev and libvpx-dev
# are gone for real (the tg_owt CMake block that consumed them no longer
# exists, confirmed zero references anywhere in this project's own
# CMakeLists.txt).
#
# Everything else from the old list (libjpeg-dev, libasound2-dev,
# libpulse-dev, the libx11-dev/libxext-dev/.../libxcomposite-dev cluster,
# libpipewire-0.3-dev, libevent-dev) is kept, even though ntgcalls' own
# CMake does fetch its own copies of X11/mesa/glib/ffmpeg/openh264
# (confirmed live via its configure output - "-- glib v2.89.0", "-- libX11
# v1.8.13", ...). The "ntgcalls vendors its own copies, so the system
# package is unneeded" theory looked solid from reading this project's own
# CMakeLists.txt alone, but three separate real CI failures across the
# first dpkg-buildpackage runs of this migration proved it wrong every
# time it was actually checked: ntgcalls/include/ntgcalls/devices/alsa_device_module.hpp
# directly #includes <alsa/asoundlib.h> (even though the matching .cpp
# only ever dlopen()s libasound.so at runtime via a LATESYM_GET symbol
# table, never linked at build time); ntgcalls' own *vendored* X11/Xlib.h
# itself failed to find X11/X.h (its downloaded X11 headers are incomplete
# on their own, evidently expecting the rest from the system's real
# libx11-dev); and ntgcalls/include/ntgcalls/utils/pulse_connection.hpp
# directly #includes <pulse/pulseaudio.h> (an earlier version of this
# comment claimed libpulse-dev was confirmed unneeded, based on checking
# only the *.cpp files, not this header - wrong, worth remembering as a
# reminder to check the .hpp too, not just the .cpp, when doing this kind
# of source-reading verification). All three are "partially vendored, not
# fully self-contained" - the vendoring reduces linking (final .so
# binaries) but not the full header closure. Given the theory has now
# failed every single time it was actually build-checked, the remaining
# untested members of the same removed cluster (libjpeg-dev/
# libpipewire-0.3-dev/libevent-dev) were restored preemptively rather than
# waiting to find each one via its own separate failing CI run (~35-45 min
# each) - no positive build confirmation either way for those three
# specifically, unlike ALSA/X11/pulse which now all have real negative
# confirmation (a genuine compile failure without them).
#
# libspdlog-dev/libfmt-dev removed - spdlog is now built from source under
# the same Clang+libc++ toolchain as PJSIP/TDLib below (Debian's own
# libspdlog1.15 is GCC+libstdc++-built, mixing it in would reintroduce the
# exact ABI-collision bug class documented in
# buildenv/rename-webrtc-openssl-symbols.sh/rename-webrtc-libsrtp-symbols.sh
# one library over). libopus-dev/libavcodec-dev/etc kept regardless of the
# theory above - tg2sip-webrtc's own CMakeLists.txt genuinely
# pkg_check_modules()s real system opus/ffmpeg (separately from whatever
# copy ntgcalls itself also fetches for its own internal use), confirmed
# live via configure output ("Checking for module 'opus'" / "-- Found
# opus, version 1.3.1").
#
# clang-<N>/libc++-<N>-dev/libc++abi-<N>-dev/libclang-rt-<N>-dev
# deliberately NOT listed here: Debian's own apt doesn't carry them
# (bookworm's apt clang is 14, too old to even compile ntgcalls' vendored
# libc++ headers - real, confirmed compile errors, not just a warning),
# they only exist via apt.llvm.org, which has to be added as an apt source
# *before* `apt-get build-dep` can resolve anything from it - see the
# "Install newer Clang" step in .github/workflows/deb-packages.yml, which
# installs them explicitly ahead of the build-dep step below rather than
# through this file.
#
# gperf/yasm/nasm kept - PJSIP still builds several of its own bundled
# third-party codecs (libsrtp, speex, resample, ...) from source in
# debian/rules, and whether any of those still need gperf/yasm/nasm for
# assembly-optimized paths hasn't been specifically checked either way
# (no CI failure yet, but per the pattern above that's not strong
# evidence on its own - just not worth removing preemptively like the
# jpeg/pipewire/libevent cluster was restored, since these were never
# actually removed to begin with).
